Title : Henry Potts
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}
'''Henry Potts''' (1810 â€“ 22 March 1884) was an English farmer, steeplechase rider, High Sheriff of Flintshire and Denbighshire, and [[cricket]]er with [[Amateur status in first-class cricket|amateur status]] who was active in 1831. He was born and died in [[Chester]]. 

==Cricket career==
He made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut in 1831 and appeared in one match as an unknown [[handedness]] [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] whose [[bowling (cricket)|bowling style]] is unknown, playing for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]]. He scored no [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 0 and took no [[wicket]]s.<ref name="CA37">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37525/37525.html |publisher=''CricketArchive'' |title=Henry Potts |accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> 
Potts was educated at [[Shrewsbury School]] and [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]]. 

==Steeplechasing==
In 1837 Potts rode at the [[Aintree]] races, which included a mount on The Duke in the Grand Liverpool Steeplechase, a precursor to the [[Grand National]]. Potts won the race but never again took part in the race. <ref> http://www.chesterstandard.co.uk/mobile/mnews/87171/did-a-north-wales-runner-win-the-first-grand-national-.aspx </ref> 

==After Sport==
In later years he was [[High Sheriff of Flintshire]] in 1852 and [[High Sheriff of Denbighshire]] in 1877.<ref>{{acad |id=PTS828H |name=Potts, Henry}}</ref>

